b'' b'' b'' b'the white house' b'' b'office of the press secretary' b'' b'_______________________________________________________________' b'' b'for immediate release\t \t \t april b'' b'' b'text of a letter from the president' b'to the speaker of the' b'house of representatives and' b'the president pro tempore of the senate' b'' b'' b'april b'' b'' b'dear mr. speaker: (dear mr. president:)' b'' b'as part of my continuing effort to keep the congress fully' b'informed, i am providing this report, consistent with section b'of the war powers resolution, to advise you of actions that i' b'have ordered in support of the united nations efforts in' b'bosnia-herzegovina.' b'' b'beginning with u.n. security council resolution of' b'september the united nations has been actively' b'addressing the crisis in the former yugoslavia. the security' b'council acted in resolution to establish a ban on all' b'unauthorized military flights over bosnia-herzegovina. there' b'have, however, been blatant violations of the ban, and villages' b'in bosnia have been bombed.' b'' b'in response to these violations, the security council decided,' b'in resolution of march to extend the ban to all' b'unauthorized flights over bosnia-herzegovina and to authorize' b'member states, acting nationally or through regional organi-' b'zations, to take all necessary measures to ensure compliance.' b"nato's north atlantic council (nac) agreed to provide nato air" b'enforcement for the no-fly zone. the u.n. secretary general' b"was notified of nato's decision to proceed with operation deny" b'flight, and an activation order was delivered to participating' b'allies.' b'' b'the united states actively supported these decisions. at my' b'direction, the joint chiefs of staff sent an execute order to' b'all u.s. forces participating in the nato force, for the conduct' b'of phased air operations to prevent flights not authorized by' b'the united nations over bosnia-herzegovina. the u.s. forces' b'initially assigned to this operation consist of f-15 and' b'12 f-18a fighter aircraft and supporting tanker aircraft.' b'these aircraft commenced enforcement operations at a.m.' b'e.d.t. on april the fighter aircraft are equipped for' b'combat to accomplish their mission and for self-defense.' b'' b'nato has positioned forces and has established combat air' b'patrol (cap) stations within the control of airborne early' b'warning (aew) aircraft. the u.s. cap aircraft will normally' b'operate from bases in italy and from an aircraft carrier in the' b'adriatic sea. unauthorized aircraft entering or approaching' b'the no-fly zone will be identified, interrogated, intercepted,' b'escorted/monitored, and turned away (in that order). if these' b'steps do not result in compliance with the no-fly zone, such' b'aircraft may be engaged on the basis of proper authorization by' b'nato military authorities and in accordance with the approved' b'' b'more' b'' b'(over)' b'' b'2' b'' b'rules of engagement, although we do not expect such action will' b'be necessary. the commander of unprofor (the united nations' b'protection force currently operating in bosnia-herzegovina) was' b'consulted to ensure that his concerns for his force were fully' b'considered before the rules of engagement were approved.' b'' b'it is not possible to predict at this time how long such' b'operations will be necessary. i have directed u.s. armed forces' b'to participate in these operations pursuant to my constitutional' b'authority as commander in chief. i am grateful for the con-' b'tinuing support that the congress has given to this effort, and' b'i look forward to continued cooperation as we move forward' b'toward attainment of our goals in this region.' b'' b'sincerely,' b'' b'' b'' b'' b'william j. clinton' b'' b'' b'' b'' b'# b'' b'' 